Greetings! We’re having an issue with our autonomous paths that we could use some guidance on. First, before I forget, here is our code: GitHub - Team-190/2k25-Robot-Code at event_RIKIN

Ok, here’s the problem: We’re using the AutoRoutine API but whenever we enable, we get a massive loop overrun of up to 400 ms. We are using the autochooser from the choreo documentation, and we are unsure how to proceed with fixing this problem. Does anyone have any suggestions?

Thanks!

posts.name: David Loh
posts.cooked: Of all of the suggestions in that thread, changing thread priority was the only one that solved our problem. We also use AdvantageKit, and haven’t had any issues with the performance of background threads with changing thread priority, so I recommend at least trying it out. However, if you’re at a competition right now, you may want to wait before trying it so you have enough time to thoroughly test.

posts.name: Krish Parmar
posts.cooked: After looking at your code, I think your issue is with the auto-chooser. Since it takes a runnable, it doesn’t load your command when it is added to the auto chooser, but when scheduled. This is probably causing your loop overruns since there is a lot to load, but I am not 100% sure.

posts.name: David Loh
posts.cooked:
I don’t think the issue is with the autochooser. The autochooser loads all paths in the RobotContainer constructor, so it is most likely not causing loop overruns on enable.

I know you expressed uncertainty over raising thread priority, but if you have enough time to test before your next competition, I recommend trying it out. We did it for a whole competition, and it eliminated nearly all of our loop overruns. That being said, if your cycle times are still close to 20 ms or you see any signs of thread starvation, like stale CAN frames or odometry that doesn’t update, you should probably switch back.

posts.name: Todd
posts.cooked:
It’s weird that so much time is unaccounted for by Tracer

image 2000×764 78.5 KB

image 2000×764 78.5 KB

image 2000×764 78.5 KB

The ‘UserCodeMS’ timer in advantagekit’s overridden main loop seems pretty concrete.

And while it’s worst at the start of autonomous, there are recurring long loops through the rest of autonomous, and even into teleop, none of which Tracer is able to identify any substantive delay in, which makes me a little suspicious of your assumption that the paths are being regenerated (plus your code seems to be fine)

image 2149×1190 138 KB

image 2149×1190 138 KB

image 2149×1190 138 KB

By adding a print, it’s easy to verify that the commands generated in your AutonomousCommands.java function are called during disabled as long as its selected in the dashboard.

The only thread I see is that while it seems to be uncaught by Tracer’s diagnostics, each one of the spikes does seem to correlate to an overrun that -is- caught by tracer, just on wildly different magnitudes (20-40ms overruns, from what I’ve seen).

The Advantagekit timing in ‘Logger’ pretty solidly accounts for the extra things advantage kit sneaks in between cycles, and none of them have a substantive magnitude (at least not substantive enough to correlate with the ~150ms overruns you’re seeing in FullCycleMS.

Pretty confusing. I wish I had something to recommend trying, I suppose I’d start with trying to turn Logger off during autonomous and see if Tracer still fires off.
